Find {= person_paper =}+ retracted academic papers (retracted {= target_period =}) where the public record establishes the retraction was for research misconduct — fabrication, falsification, image manipulation, or plagiarism — by the named author (not honest error or paper-mill bulk retraction); supply at least {= url =} URLs per (person, paper) case.

Requirements:
- The source page must contain evidence that this specific paper, by this specific person, was retracted — e.g., the retraction date, the explicit retraction language ("the article was retracted"), or the retraction notice itself. The page must identify the paper (by title or DOI) and the named person (as an author).
- The source page must establish that the retraction was for research misconduct — fabrication, falsification, image manipulation, or plagiarism — applied to this specific paper. Institutional softening language ("data integrity concerns", "loss of confidence in the conclusions") may register as misconduct framing when surrounding context makes the misconduct attribution clear; ambiguous standalone phrasing without clarifying context does not. The misconduct finding ought to apply to the named person — papers retracted because OTHER co-authors committed misconduct, while the named person was personally cleared, are weaker evidence.
